04209nam a22006375i 9780292736429DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20211988txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927364297 a10.7560/7206022doi  a(DE-B1597)588800  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aGN360b.A32 1988 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a573.22191 aAdams, Richard Newbold, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Eighth Day :bSocial Evolution as the Self-Organization of Energy /cRichard Newbold Adams. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©1988  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures and Tables -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- t1. Preliminaries -- t2. Energy Process -- t3. Energy Dynamics -- t4. Self-Organization -- t5. Culture -- t6. Domestication -- t7. Natural Selection -- t8. Boundary Dynamics -- t9. Civilization -- t10. Humanities -- t11. Expansion In Social Hierarchy: A Model -- t12. Energy and Industrialization -- tPostscript: Development and Contemporary Social Evolution -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCan human social evolution be described in terms common to other sciences, most specifically, as an energy process? The Eighth Day reflects a conviction that the human trajectory, for all its uniqueness and indeterminism, will never be satisfactorily understood until it is framed in dynamics that are common to all of nature. The problem in doing this, however, lies in ourselves. The major social theories have failed to treat human social evolution as a component of broader natural processes. The Eighth Day argues that the energy process provides a basis for explaining, comparing, and measuring complex social evolution. Using traditional ecological energy flow studies as background, society is conceived as a self-organization of energy. This perspective enables Adams to analyze society in term of the natural selection of self-organizing energy forms and the trigger processes basic to it. Domestication, civilization, socioeconomic development, and the regulation of contemporary industrial nation-states serve to illustrate the approach. A principal aim is to explore the limitation that energy process imposes on human social evolution as well as to clarify the alternatives that it allows. Richly informed by contemporary anthropological historicism, sociobiology, and Marxism, The Eighth Day avoids simple reductionism and denies facile ideological categorization. Adams builds on work in nonequilibrium thermodynamics and theoretical biology and brings three decades of his own work to an analysis of human society that demands an extreme materialism in which human thought and action find a central place.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aForce and energy. 0aSelf-organizing systems. 0aSocial evolution. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/72060240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292736429423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292736429/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK